web_results.snippet: Nutmeg is the seed, or the ground spice derived from that seed, of several tree species of the genus Myristica; fragrant nutmeg or true nutmeg is a dark-leaved evergreen tree cultivated for two spices derived from its fruit: nutmeg, from its seed, and mace, from the seed covering.

related_questions.question: What nut is nutmeg made from?
related_questions.snippet: Nutmeg is not a nut but a seed of the Myristica plant. The fragrant nutmeg plant produces a golden-hued, apricot-like fruit. The kernel of that fruit is where nutmeg and mace, the outer skin of the nutmeg kernel called the aril, are sourced.

related_questions.question: Is nutmeg just like cinnamon?
related_questions.snippet: Cinnamon has a very similar flavor profile to nutmeg, so it works great as a substitute. Cinnamon does have a more pungent flavor than nutmeg, so it's best to start with half the amount of cinnamon than called for nutmeg and taste along the way to determine if more needs to be added.

related_questions.question: Does nutmeg make you sleepy?
related_questions.snippet: Promotes sleep It is still a common practice to add a pinch of nutmeg to warm milk to promote better sleep. Nutmeg contains phytonutrients that help increase serotonin levels and promote relaxation.

answer_box.title: Nutmeg | Tree, Uses, History, Description, & Facts | Britannica
answer_box.snippet: The spice nutmeg has a distinctive pungent fragrance and a warm slightly sweet taste; it is used to flavour many kinds of baked goods, confections, puddings, potatoes, meats, sausages, sauces, vegetables, and such beverages as eggnog. The fleshy arils surrounding the nutmeg seed are the source of the spice mace.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Nutmeg Do To Your Body?
buttons.title: 8 Science-Backed Benefits of Nutmeg - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Nutmeg is rich in anti-inflammatory compounds called monoterpenes, including sabinene, terpineol, and pinene. These may help reduce inflammation in your body and benefit those with inflammatory conditions ( 1 ).
snippet_highlighted_words: may help reduce inflammation in your body and benefit those with inflammatory conditions

buttons.subtitle: What Kind Of High Does Nutmeg Give You?
buttons.title: Nutmeg - an overview | ScienceDirect Topics
buttons.snippet: Nutmeg contains psychoactive a variety of chemicals including myristicin, elemicin, eugenol and safrole which are thought to be responsible for its psychoactive properties. Nutmeg intoxication causes a variety of CNS effects including hallucinations, confusion, drowsiness and incoherent speech.
snippet_highlighted_words: hallucinations, confusion, drowsiness and incoherent speech

buttons.title: Nutmeg is a drug? | Office for Science and Society - McGill University
buttons.snippet: Its essential oil has been used topically to treat arthritis pain and orally with small amounts of honey or sugar, to alleviate gastrointestinal problems. However, nutmeg contains myristicin which is chemically similar to MDMA or “ecstasy,” and can cause hallucinations when ingested in large doses.

buttons.subtitle: What Are The Side Effects Of Nutmeg
buttons.title: Nutmeg: Health Benefits, Side Effects, Uses, Dose & Precautions - RxList
buttons.snippet: Long-term use of nutmeg in doses of 120 mg or more daily has been linked to hallucinations and other mental side effects. People who have taken larger doses of nutmeg have experienced nausea, dry mouth, dizziness, irregular heartbeat, agitation and hallucinations. Other serious side effects have included death.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Nutmeg Taste Like?
buttons.title: A Guide To Mace | What Is Mace? | Tilda Rice UK
buttons.snippet: What does mace taste like? Mace is milder and sweeter, with a hint of citrus, cinnamon, black pepper and pine. It's more delicate than nutmeg, and that's why it's commonly used in pastries, cakes, doughnuts, fish dishes, soups and casseroles.
